have every case authorised

128
00:08:20,629 --> 00:08:21,929
before I launch an investigation.

129
00:08:21,930 --> 00:08:24,710
And does the fraud squad know
you're going after Stone?

130
00:08:24,810 --> 00:08:27,550
The information I've been given
is that they're planning a job,

131
00:08:27,650 --> 00:08:29,950
I can't to this stage determine
whether it's fraud or not.

132
00:08:29,951 --> 00:08:32,049
Don't play games with me, lnspector.

133
00:08:32,050 --> 00:08:35,030
I'm just an old-fashioned copper.
Find the bad guys. Put 'em away.

134
00:08:35,130 --> 00:08:37,670
Some of us have to get
our hands dirty.

135
00:08:37,770 --> 00:08:41,000
And that's how you intend to conduct
the case, is it? Get dirty?

136
00:08:42,120 --> 00:08:43,190
If I have to.

137
00:08:43,290 --> 00:08:46,390
I will not have this department
brought into disrepute.

138
00:08:46,490 --> 00:08:49,310
Everything gets done by the
book, the same book I'll be

139
00:08:49,410 --> 00:08:51,670
throwing at you if I find out
you've been cutting corners.

140
00:08:51,770 --> 00:08:53,390
Yes, Ma'am.

141
00:08:53,490 --> 00:08:55,070
I mean it, lnspector.

142
00:08:55,170 --> 00:08:57,750
You have to catch him
with the cash in his hand.

143
00:08:57,850 --> 00:09:01,910
Any room for doubt and you'll end up
embarrassing us all.

144
00:09:02,010 --> 00:09:05,280
Oh, I'll catch him, Ma'am.
I guarantee it.

145
00:09:06,560 --> 00:09:10,830
OK, so our new mark is
Linda Runcorn.

146
00:09:10,930 --> 00:09:14,670
The story is that she's the CEO of
an online restaurant and hotel guide.

147
00:09:14,770 --> 00:09:18,470
It's got a huge tourist readership,
so it's very influential.

148
00:09:18,570 --> 00:09:22,070
However, excellence is not the best
way to guarantee a good review.

149
00:09:22,170 --> 00:09:25,549
The larger chains escape, but
she tells the smaller hotels

150
00:09:25,550 --> 00:09:28,049
and family restaurants that if they
don't make it worth her while,

151
00:09:28,050 --> 00:09:30,049
she'll put them out of
business.

152
00:09:30,050 --> 00:09:33,510
- Worth her while by handing
over cash? - Precisely.

153
00:09:33,610 --> 00:09:36,110
The smaller hotels and restaurants
survive on reputation.

154
00:09:36,210 --> 00:09:42,150
She operates on fear, and once she's
got hold of you, she bleeds you dry.

155
00:09:42,250 --> 00:09:45,190
Character traits? A bully.
She sucks up to the bigger chains,

156
00:09:45,290 --> 00:09:49,030
while bullying the smaller clients
who can't afford to fight back. Nasty.

157
00:09:49,130 --> 00:09:51,710
- What's our way in?
- Her mum's family, the Toppings.

158
00:09:51,810 --> 00:09:55,230
Had a bit of land and a noble
line going back centuries,

159
00:09:55,330 --> 00:09:59,190
but they cut off her grandmother,
Helen Topping, without a penny

160
00:09:59,290 --> 00:10:00,990
when she married a builder.

161
00:10:01,090 --> 00:10:02,990
Seems the family thought
he was beneath her.

162
00:10:03,090 --> 00:10:06,070
But to this day, Linda wears
a bracelet given to her

163
00:10:06,170 --> 00:10:10,430
by her Grandmother which bears
the Topping family crest.

164
00:10:10,530 --> 00:10:13,150
So what's the game?
An inheritance scam?

165
00:10:13,250 --> 00:10:16,270
Yeah. We use a long-lost relative
Linda's never heard of.

166
00:10:16,370 --> 00:10:19,670
One of the Toppings. A maiden aunt
who died without making a will,

167
00:10:19,770 --> 00:10:23,510
leaving behind an estate which
Linda is the sole heir to.

168
00:10:23,610 --> 00:10:27,360
Which just happens to be worth
a small fortune. Exactly.

169
00:10:36,200 --> 00:10:39,040
Yeah, I'm here.
I'll call you when I'm done.

170
00:10:43,480 --> 00:10:45,030
- Miss Runcorn?
- Yes.

171
00:10:45,130 --> 00:10:48,750
Hello. I'm Holly Patterson,
Greyshot Genealogy.

172
00:10:48,850 --> 00:10:50,870
I was rather surprised
to get your letter.

173
00:10:50,871 --> 00:10:53,569
- Oh?
- How did you find me?

174
00:10:53,570 --> 00:10:56,310
- The voting register.
- Did I ask for water?

175
00:10:56,410 --> 00:10:59,290
For heaven's sake, just put it down.
We'll call you when we want something.

176
00:10:59,390 --> 00:11:03,150
They fuss all over you, then when
you actually want something,

177
00:11:03,250 --> 00:11:04,750
when you want to actually
order something,

178
00:11:04,751 --> 00:11:07,849
they're nowhere to be bloody seen.
Quite.

179
00:11:07,850 --> 00:11:10,590
So, what's this potentially
exciting news exactly?

180
00:11:10,690 --> 00:11:13,990
Well, every few months,
the Treasury releases

181
00:11:13,991 --> 00:11:16,289
a list of estates that are intestate.

182
00:11:16,290 --> 00:11:19,230
- That means... - People who died
without leaving a will. Yes. Yes.

183
00:11:19,330 --> 00:11:21,830
You're one of those bloody
heir hunters, aren't you?

184
00:11:21,930 --> 00:11:24,910
Oh, well, we prefer
probate investigators.

185
00:11:25,010 --> 00:11:28,230
All the same thing,
like ambulance chasers.

186
00:11:28,330 --> 00:11:31,190
I can't imagine what you
found on my father's side,

187
00:11:31,191 --> 00:11:32,689
they didn't have two
pennies to rub together.

188
00:11:32,690 --> 00:11:34,030
What is it?
A tin bath?

189
00:11:34,130 --> 00:11:36,670
Well, actually, it's a relative
on your mother's side.

190
00:11:36,770 --> 00:11:38,990
- Oh. My mother's side?
- Yes, the Toppings...

191
00:11:39,090 --> 00:11:45,430
Now, this is your great-aunt Irene.
Irene Topping. Excuse me.

192
00:11:45,530 --> 00:11:48,950
Sorry, I just need to check this.

193
00:11:49,050 --> 00:11:52,350
She's the sister of your
maternal grandmother.

194
00:11:52,450 --> 00:11:54,870
Now, your great-aunt passed away.

195
00:11:54,970 --> 00:11:57,790
She was childless, she never married
and she didn't leave a will.

196
00:11:57,890 --> 00:11:59,950
So her estate passed to
the next in line.

197
00:12:00,050 --> 00:12:05,150
- Which is you. -Me?
- Yes. It appears so.

198
00:12:05,250 --> 00:12:08,230
Well, I don't suppose there's
anything to get too excited about.

199
00:12:08,330 --> 00:12:10,170
I never really believed
all those rumours

200
00:12:10,171 --> 00:12:12,369
about my mother's
aristocratic family.

201
00:12:12,370 --> 00:12:16,190
The old bag probably left me a
tatty old armchair and some cats.

202
00:12:16,290 --> 00:12:21,010
Well, she actually left you
jewellery and property

203
00:12:21,109 --> 00:12:24,209
worth in the region of £4.7 million.

204
00:12:24,210 --> 00:12:28,190
And, as far as we can tell,
you are the sole heir.

205
00:12:28,290 --> 00:12:32,150
Well, that's different.

206
00:12:32,250 --> 00:12:36,310
I mean, obviously, I am devastated
about poor old Great-Aunt Irene.

207
00:12:36,410 --> 00:12:39,390
But... Sorry,
did you say 4.7 million?

208
00:12:39,490 --> 00:12:43,430
- I did.
- O-M-G.

209
00:12:43,530 --> 00:12:45,750
Well, it was a 
pleasure to meet you.

210
00:12:45,850 --> 00:12:48,040
You'll be hearing from us soon.
Bye-bye.

211
00:12:51,600 --> 00:12:54,350
Yeah, it's me. Done.

212
00:12:54,450 --> 00:12:58,080
- Hook, line and sinker.
- OK, good. See you back here.

213
00:13:16,240 --> 00:13:17,310
Well?

214
00:13:17,410 --> 00:13:20,470
Some old rubbish about an old
aunt leaving her a fortune.

215
00:13:20,570 --> 00:13:23,800
All right, stay on it.

216
00:13:31,000 --> 00:13:32,320
Katherine Farmer.

217
00:13:33,400 --> 00:13:36,390
We haven't seen you for a while.

218
00:13:36,490 --> 00:13:37,670
Still picking pockets?

219
00:13:37,770 --> 00:13:40,390
No idea what you're
banging on about, mate.

220
00:13:40,490 --> 00:13:41,670
